    "concept": "Isoniazid inhibits pyridoxine (vitamin B6)-dependent enzymes and increases renal excretion of pyridoxine, leading to a functional B6 deficiency that manifests as a symmetric, stocking-glove peripheral neuropathy. Prophylactic pyridoxine supplementation is routinely given with isoniazid therapy to prevent this complication, especially in patients at higher risk (e.g., malnourished, diabetic, pregnant, or alcohol-use patients).",
    "discriminator": "The temporal link to isoniazid therapy for TB is the key clue that identifies pyridoxine deficiency as the cause, distinguishing it from other vitamin-deficiency neuropathies.",
    "mnemonic": "INH = Inhibits Neurochemical Handling of B6 — remember to give pyridoxine (B6) with isoniazid."
