    "explanation": "Exertional heat stroke is defined by a core temperature typically above 40 C (104 F) accompanied by central nervous system dysfunction. This patient's somnolence and disorientation to place and time constitute altered mental status, and the elevated creatine kinase with rising creatinine reflects early end-organ injury (rhabdomyolysis, acute kidney injury). Heat exhaustion is hyperthermia WITHOUT altered mental status or end-organ damage, so the presence of CNS dysfunction and organ injury excludes it. Sweating may persist in exertional (as opposed to classic) heat stroke, so intact diaphoresis does not rule it out. Vasovagal syncope causes brief loss of consciousness with rapid full recovery and no hyperthermia. Sepsis is unlikely without an infectious source or hemodynamic instability in a previously healthy young athlete with a clear exertional trigger. Cocaine intoxication can cause hyperthermia but would typically produce dilated pupils, hypertension, and agitation rather than this exertional picture. Management is immediate rapid cooling and supportive care.",
